{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499792"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:03:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:03:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1563"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1563"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.77,0.13,0.05,0.04,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1563"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32213"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1563"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1563"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17887"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"832"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2161"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2185"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32213","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/32213"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old woman presents with a tender swelling on the medial aspect of her left eye. It has been present for a few days and occasionally there is a small amount of purulent discharge present. (Image)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nasolacrimal duct obstruction","Keratoacanthoma","Hordeolum","Chalazion","Foreign body reaction"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe site of this swelling is over the nasolacrimal duct, the blockage of which may be known as \u003Cstrong\u003Enasolacrimal duct obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E (NLDO) or dacryostenosis. The patient may have tearing, discharge, and a painful lump at the medial edge of the eye. This condition may be congenital or acquired. Elderly women are more susceptible, likely due to the smaller diameter of the duct which narrows over time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment is with warm compresses and massage. For infected cases (dacryocystitis), topical or systemic antibiotics may be used depending on severity. In recurrent cases, surgery may be indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough this mass does have a similar appearance to a keratoacanthoma, it would develop over months rather than days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHordeolum or stye is an acute infection of an eyelash follicle. Chalazion is a granuloma caused by leakage of oil from a meibomian gland that has a blocked pore.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA foreign body reaction would affect the cornea rather than the epithelium surrounding the orbit.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Nasolacrimal duct obstruction can be manifest by a swelling on the medial aspect of the eye."],"references":["Perez Y, Patel B, Mendez M. Nasolacrimal Duct Obstruction. StatPearls. 2020.","Sun M, Huang S, Huilgol S, Silva D. Eyelid lesions in general practice. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2019;48(8):509-514."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17887"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1563"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19062"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19062"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d50a2b37-523d-4bf7-b711-864ae44f70ab.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d50a2b37-523d-4bf7-b711-864ae44f7